so I figured I would just go
with that here.

00:26:31.599 --> 00:26:34.515
I figured that would have the
added benefit of:

00:26:34.515 --> 00:26:36.670
If you don't vote for this
book,

00:26:36.670 --> 00:26:39.160
then I'll just be the kid who
made a fool of himself and read

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:41.069
with a Russian accent in front
of everybody.

00:26:41.069 --> 00:26:43.670
So, I know you don't want to do
that to me.

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:51.009
Yeah. Okay, I think. All right.
So here we go.

00:26:51.009 --> 00:26:53.439
This is Alex kind of
introducing himself at the

00:26:53.439 --> 00:26:56.316
beginning of the book:
"I dig Negroes,

00:26:56.316 --> 00:27:00.352
particularly Michael Jackson.
I dig to disseminate very much

00:27:00.352 --> 00:27:02.829
currency at famous nightclubs in
Odessa.

00:27:02.829 --> 00:27:06.839
Lamborghini Countaches are
excellent so are cappuccinos.

00:27:06.839 --> 00:27:09.743
Many girls want to be carnal
with me in many good

00:27:09.743 --> 00:27:12.343
arrangements,
notwithstanding the Inebriated

00:27:12.343 --> 00:27:14.976
Kangaroo,
the Gorky Tickle and the

00:27:14.976 --> 00:27:18.354
Unyielding Zookeeper.
If you want to know why so many

00:27:18.354 --> 00:27:21.398
girls want to be with me,
it is because I am very premium

00:27:21.398 --> 00:27:24.409
person to be with.
I am homely and also severely

00:27:24.409 --> 00:27:26.730
funny and these are winning
things.

00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:30.097
But nonetheless I know many
people who dig rapid cars and

00:27:30.097 --> 00:27:32.837
famous discotheques.
There are so many here who

00:27:32.837 --> 00:27:35.618
perform the Sputnik Bosom
Dalliance--which is always

00:27:35.618 --> 00:27:38.508
terminated with a slimy
underface--that I cannot tally

00:27:38.508 --> 00:27:41.526
them on all of my hands.
There are even many people

00:27:41.526 --> 00:27:44.098
named Alex.
(Three in my house alone!) That

00:27:44.098 --> 00:27:47.792
is why I was so effervescent to
go to Lutsk and translate for

00:27:47.792 --> 00:27:51.599
Jonathan Safran Foer.
It would be unordinary.

00:27:51.599 --> 00:27:54.530
So that's said,
and a fool proudly made.

00:27:54.530 --> 00:27:56.460
That's it.
Thank you.

00:28:04.079 --> 00:28:06.510
Roger:
Well, it's really

00:28:06.510 --> 00:28:09.870
unfortunate to have to go after
that, but hi.

00:28:09.870 --> 00:28:12.044
My name's Roger.
I'm presenting for Amina's

00:28:12.044 --> 00:28:14.660
section, and we're doing Dave
Eggers' What is the What

00:28:14.660 --> 00:28:17.370
(and you can't see the
"What" because it's 20% off;

00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:20.699
plug, plug).
And, I guess,

00:28:20.699 --> 00:28:23.864
rather than try to sum up the
book myself, I'll use not the

00:28:23.864 --> 00:28:27.085
author's but the person about
whom the book is written's own

00:28:27.085 --> 00:28:30.305
words: "What is the What
is the soulful account of my

00:28:30.305 --> 00:28:32.899
life,
from the time I was separated

00:28:32.899 --> 00:28:36.645
from my family in Marial Bai
---- to the thirteen years I

00:28:36.645 --> 00:28:39.789
spent in Ethiopian and Kenyan
refugee camps,

00:28:39.789 --> 00:28:43.218
to my encounter with vibrant
Western cultures beginning in

00:28:43.218 --> 00:28:46.767
Atlanta, to the generosity and
challenges that I encountered

00:28:46.767 --> 00:28:49.257
elsewhere.
So, just to add a little

00:28:49.257 --> 00:28:52.787
bit to that, What is the What
is a story of a Sudanese

00:28:52.787 --> 00:28:56.355
refugee in the United States.
And in the course of telling

00:28:56.355 --> 00:28:59.486
it, he reads an account from his
life back in Africa,

00:28:59.486 --> 00:29:02.737
to stories here in the United
States, and everything in

00:29:02.737 --> 00:29:05.130
between.
As for reasons why you should

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:08.463
want to vote for it or read it,
I think the first thing which

00:29:08.463 --> 00:29:11.518
many of us in the section
realize about the book is just

00:29:11.518 --> 00:29:14.952
that it's really engaging.
It's written in a way that's,

00:29:14.952 --> 00:29:17.431
I would say,
kind of refreshing compared to

00:29:17.431 --> 00:29:20.915
some of the other more--how to
put it?--complex authors that

00:29:20.915 --> 00:29:23.556
we've read,
in that it's just really

00:29:23.556 --> 00:29:27.869
accessible and really just an
easy read that's deeply human.

00:29:27.869 --> 00:29:30.413
You feel like you're having a
conversation with the guy,

00:29:30.413 --> 00:29:33.048
and (even though the guy is
actually having a conversation

00:29:33.048 --> 00:29:35.919
with Dave Eggers,
so maybe that's why you get

00:29:35.919 --> 00:29:39.015
that impression,
but at any rate) it's also a

00:29:39.015 --> 00:29:41.829
book which manages to address
really,

00:29:41.829 --> 00:29:45.913
really serious current issues
such as civil war,

00:29:45.913 --> 00:29:49.650
genocide, alienation in
American society,

00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:52.257
but do so in a way that's
simultaneously really poignant

00:29:52.257 --> 00:29:53.490
and inspiring,
but also,

00:29:53.490 --> 00:29:55.886
actually, funny.
It's not a book that you're

00:29:55.886 --> 00:29:58.829
going to read and be depressed
by, even though you will come

00:29:58.829 --> 00:30:01.673
from it having really felt that
you're dealing with really

00:30:01.673 --> 00:30:04.879
significant material,
which I thought is really cool,

00:30:04.879 --> 00:30:08.390
and we thought was really cool.
It's also--just going on to

00:30:08.390 --> 00:30:11.420
the whole contemporary thing--
it's written by one of the best

00:30:11.420 --> 00:30:15.339
contemporary authors out there.
He was nominated for a Pulitzer;

00:30:15.339 --> 00:30:17.591
he was a Pulitzer Prize
finalist, I think,

00:30:17.591 --> 00:30:19.378
last year, 2007.
(I'm not sure,

00:30:19.378 --> 00:30:22.513
and if I got that wrong and
someone here is a big Eggers

00:30:22.513 --> 00:30:24.680
fan, I'm terribly sorry.) But
yeah;

00:30:24.680 --> 00:30:27.523
he's great.
And, in a course where we're

00:30:27.523 --> 00:30:31.778
doing from 1945 to the present,
I think it's good to have a

00:30:31.778 --> 00:30:34.712
really strong,
really contemporary author

00:30:34.712 --> 00:30:37.789
represented.
So, that's another cool thing.

00:30:37.789 --> 00:30:40.385
Another thing which I think
would be really cool about

00:30:40.385 --> 00:30:43.471
reading this book is that - it's
not your standard academic book

00:30:43.471 --> 00:30:45.785
at all.
You're not going to find this

00:30:45.785 --> 00:30:48.661
book on any syllabus,
but it still really merits

00:30:48.661 --> 00:30:52.272
being read in that sort of a
context because of the depth of

00:30:52.272 --> 00:30:54.660
the material that's being
covered,

00:30:54.660 --> 00:30:56.789
because of the way it's written.
Really, there are some

00:30:56.789 --> 00:30:58.490
beautiful descriptions with
beautiful language.

00:30:58.490 --> 00:31:01.079
And, well, for any other reason
that you'd want to read a book

00:31:01.079 --> 00:31:02.819
in a class, it can serve that
function,

00:31:02.819 --> 00:31:05.580
and yet you'd probably more
like to hear about it in a

00:31:05.580 --> 00:31:09.008
coffee shop or in a restaurant.
So, I think that's a pretty

00:31:09.008 --> 00:31:11.730
cool opportunity which this
would give us.

00:31:11.730 --> 00:31:13.891
As far as tying in to the
course matters,

00:31:13.891 --> 00:31:15.660
this book is a great,
great study,

00:31:15.660 --> 00:31:18.370
and, I would think,
an unprecedented study,

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:20.630
as far as the Identity Plot
goes,

00:31:20.630 --> 00:31:23.706
for our class,
because as a black African the

00:31:23.706 --> 00:31:27.830
protagonist is identified not by
his ethnicity in the United

00:31:27.830 --> 00:31:30.109
States,
but by his race.

00:31:30.109 --> 00:31:33.515
And, as is shown in a really
very interesting,

00:31:33.515 --> 00:31:36.768
I guess, scene,
at the very beginning of the

00:31:36.768 --> 00:31:39.074
book,
where he's being robbed by a

00:31:39.074 --> 00:31:42.031
black man who says to him,
"Oh, well, we're brothers

00:31:42.031 --> 00:31:45.279
because you're African" and at
the same time derides,

00:31:45.279 --> 00:31:47.863
only refers to him as African
and actually mislabels him as

00:31:47.863 --> 00:31:50.674
Nigerian when he's Sudanese.
So, it really offers some

00:31:50.674 --> 00:31:53.740
really interesting perspective
into issues of race,

00:31:53.740 --> 00:31:58.702
issues of ethnicity,
and just a totally new look at

00:31:58.702 --> 00:32:01.680
American society from,
yeah,

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:04.390
a perspective that we're not
really used to.

00:32:04.390 --> 00:32:06.259
I guess, yeah,
that basically covers that.

00:32:06.259 --> 00:32:08.667
As far as some other,
maybe a little bit sillier

00:32:08.667 --> 00:32:11.500
things, this is a great date
book for those of you who either

00:32:11.500 --> 00:32:13.529
are dating or are looking to be
dating.

00:32:13.529 --> 00:32:16.376
It's a book that people are
reading all of the time,

00:32:16.376 --> 00:32:18.329
and, even if they aren't
reading,

00:32:18.329 --> 00:32:21.147
then you can really wow them
with just your knowledge of

00:32:21.147 --> 00:32:23.811
contemporary literature,
and to say nothing of your

00:32:23.811 --> 00:32:26.627
concern for the people who are
struggling in America and

00:32:26.627 --> 00:32:29.779
abroad.
So, really, that's a big plug.

00:32:29.779 --> 00:32:32.549
And it's also won a bunch of
awards.

00:32:32.549 --> 00:32:36.247
It was a finalist for the
National Book Critics Circle

00:32:36.247 --> 00:32:39.037
Award for Fiction,
which I think is good,

00:32:39.037 --> 00:32:42.505
and the guy from Barnes &amp;
Noble would not let me leave

00:32:42.505 --> 00:32:45.210
the counter because he liked it
so much, and he is a good judge.

00:32:45.210 --> 00:32:47.592
So, those are some really
good plugs but as far as a

00:32:47.592 --> 00:32:50.320
weakness, you might notice it's
a little bit bigger than some of

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:53.736
the other books that we've read,
but I promise you that that's

00:32:53.736 --> 00:32:55.677
okay.
You fly through the pages,

00:32:55.677 --> 00:32:58.493
and just to give you a sense of
why you do that,

00:32:58.493 --> 00:33:01.130
I'll read to you a section from
the book.

00:33:01.130 --> 00:33:03.571
It's actually the last
paragraph of the book,

00:33:03.571 --> 00:33:06.846
but it's not like one of those
spoilers, like "And then your

00:33:06.846 --> 00:33:07.953
mother died."
No.

00:33:07.953 --> 00:33:09.484
It actually,
really, I think,

00:33:09.484 --> 00:33:12.380
is very fitting to read,
now, because it's kind of his

00:33:12.380 --> 00:33:14.730
plug for why you should read his
book,

00:33:14.730 --> 00:33:17.110
or at least it's a description
of why he tells this story.

00:33:17.110 --> 00:33:20.728
So here we go.
Whatever I do,

00:33:20.728 --> 00:33:23.660
however I find a way to live,
I will tell these stories.

00:33:23.660 --> 00:33:26.212
I have spoken to every person I
have encountered these last

00:33:26.212 --> 00:33:27.929
difficult days,
and every person who has

00:33:27.929 --> 00:33:30.349
entered this club during these
awful morning hours,

00:33:30.349 --> 00:33:32.689
because to do anything else
would be something less than

00:33:32.689 --> 00:33:34.346
human.
I speak to these people,

00:33:34.346 --> 00:33:36.869
and I speak to you,
because I cannot help it.

00:33:36.869 --> 00:33:39.471
It gives me strength,
almost unbelievable strength,

00:33:39.471 --> 00:33:41.982
to know that you are there.
I covet your eyes,

00:33:41.982 --> 00:33:44.490
your ears, the collapsible
space between us.

00:33:44.490 --> 00:33:46.430
How blessed are we to have each
other.

00:33:46.430 --> 00:33:49.794
I am alive, and you are alive,
so we must fill the air with

00:33:49.794 --> 00:33:51.718
our words.
I will fill today,

00:33:51.718 --> 00:33:55.130
tomorrow, every day until I am
taken back to God.

00:33:55.130 --> 00:33:57.803
I will tell these stories to
people who will listen and to

00:33:57.803 --> 00:34:00.664
people who don't want to listen,
to people who seek me out and

00:34:00.664 --> 00:34:03.250
to those who run.
All the while I will know that

00:34:03.250 --> 00:34:05.492
you are there.
How can I pretend that you do

00:34:05.492 --> 00:34:07.215
not exist?
It would be almost as

00:34:07.215 --> 00:34:10.350
impossible as you pretending
that I do not exist.

00:34:10.350 --> 00:34:11.030
Thanks.

00:34:18.170 --> 00:34:19.030
Professor Amy
Hungerford: Okay.

00:34:19.030 --> 00:34:22.076
Vote.
If this were really a high-tech

00:34:22.076 --> 00:34:24.378
classroom, we'd have a little
console for you,

00:34:24.378 --> 00:34:26.630
and you'd be voting online,
but we don't.

00:34:26.630 --> 00:34:29.810
Okay. Okay.
Anyone need a ballot?

00:34:34.560 --> 00:34:38.420
Okay. Rank them 1,2, 3.
TAs get to vote, too.

00:34:38.420 --> 00:34:39.320
Yes, you do.

00:34:57.610 --> 00:35:00.260
And when you're finished,
pass them to the aisles.

00:35:00.260 --> 00:35:01.660
Can I borrow your pencil?

00:35:06.120 --> 00:35:07.190
I am voting too.

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:49.620
Okay. Everybody voted?
Okay, TFs.

00:35:49.620 --> 00:35:53.430
Everybody done?
Pass them over.

00:35:57.230 --> 00:35:59.760
Okay.
We will see them in a moment.

00:36:03.389 --> 00:36:07.449
Well, let me say it's a tough
act to follow you guys so

00:36:07.449 --> 00:36:11.510
congratulations to all the
people who pitched books,

00:36:11.510 --> 00:36:15.795
although I have to say I am a
little hurt at the implied

00:36:15.795 --> 00:36:18.670
criticism.
Long?

00:36:18.670 --> 00:36:20.780
Long?
Hard?

00:36:20.780 --> 00:36:24.157
Boring?
I don't recognize my own

00:36:24.157 --> 00:36:25.825
syllabus.
Maybe the long,

00:36:25.825 --> 00:36:28.059
but not the hard and the
boring.

00:36:28.059 --> 00:36:31.300
So, we will see what that next
book will be.

00:36:31.300 --> 00:36:37.942
Now, I have exactly five
minutes, so what I think I want

00:36:37.942 --> 00:36:45.260
to do is just say something very
quick about loss in this book.

00:36:45.260 --> 00:36:48.499
I put this quote up on the
board: "Need can blossom into

00:36:48.499 --> 00:36:50.619
all the compensation it
requires."

00:36:50.619 --> 00:36:56.243
That little blurb,
I think, encapsulates this

00:36:56.243 --> 00:37:02.291
novel's meditation on loss.
I asked you last time to think

00:37:02.291 --> 00:37:06.741
about where Ruth's voice comes
from, what situation we can

00:37:06.741 --> 00:37:09.079
imagine,
and there are a bunch of

00:37:09.079 --> 00:37:12.716
different theories that critics
have put forward about where

00:37:12.716 --> 00:37:15.860
Ruth is and from where we hear
her voice coming.

00:37:15.860 --> 00:37:18.734
One is that she's dead and
she's speaking to us from the

00:37:18.734 --> 00:37:22.159
afterlife, that she really,
somehow, did die in the lake

00:37:22.159 --> 00:37:26.454
that day, that she fell off the
bridge, or somehow the bridge is

00:37:26.454 --> 00:37:29.250
a metaphor for her passage into
death.

00:37:29.250 --> 00:37:34.407
Or that this is an adult Ruth,
living who knows where,

00:37:34.407 --> 00:37:39.468
or just as a transient,
who has written this account,

00:37:39.468 --> 00:37:42.679
or who speaks to us,
somehow.

00:37:42.679 --> 00:37:47.043
I think that quotation from
Marilynne Robinson that I gave

00:37:47.043 --> 00:37:52.139
you at the end of last lecture,
about how she aims to speak in

00:37:52.139 --> 00:37:57.278
the voice of the consciousness
of the person--not necessarily

00:37:57.278 --> 00:38:02.416
the words that they would use if
they were to write their own

00:38:02.416 --> 00:38:07.555
account--suggests that what she
is getting at doesn't require

00:38:07.555 --> 00:38:12.780
that kind of historical
explanation to account for it,

00:38:12.780 --> 00:38:17.690
that she doesn't want us to
have to think of Ruth speaking

00:38:17.690 --> 00:38:24.979
from a particular place,
which is also a way to say that

00:38:24.979 --> 00:38:32.329
Ruth is gone;
somehow Ruth is absent from us.

00:38:32.329 --> 00:38:37.699
And this relates to my point
last time about how identity is

00:38:37.699 --> 00:38:41.495
imagined as voice.
Ruth, the historical Ruth,

00:38:41.495 --> 00:38:45.293
the character Ruth,
a Ruth that we could situate in

00:38:45.293 --> 00:38:48.179
any concrete position in the
world,

00:38:48.179 --> 00:38:52.849
has vanished from the frame of
this novel.

00:38:52.849 --> 00:38:55.690
What we're left with is her
voice.

00:38:55.690 --> 00:39:00.516
The logic here is that
vanishing makes the voice

00:39:00.516 --> 00:39:06.638
totally present;
that full human presence is in

00:39:06.638 --> 00:39:13.117
the voice, somehow inherent.
That's why there are all of

00:39:13.117 --> 00:39:18.185
these meditations on what would
happen if various people either

00:39:18.185 --> 00:39:21.210
did disappear or didn't
disappear.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:27.207
So, when Ruth meditates on what
it would be like for her to

00:39:27.207 --> 00:39:31.447
leave Sylvie,
she says, "I did not want to

00:39:31.447 --> 00:39:35.789
grow gigantic and multiple to
Sylvie."

00:39:35.789 --> 00:39:39.195
Her sense is that,
by leaving Sylvie,

00:39:39.195 --> 00:39:44.210
her absence would become
enormous, and she herself,

00:39:44.210 --> 00:39:48.724
in a kind of negative presence,
would become larger than she

00:39:48.724 --> 00:39:52.702
is, and this is how Ruth feels
about her own mother's

00:39:52.702 --> 00:39:56.109
disappearance,
that when her mother

00:39:56.109 --> 00:40:01.994
disappeared, what she got in
return was the compensation of

00:40:01.994 --> 00:40:06.082
memory: sharp,
specific, evocative,

00:40:06.082 --> 00:40:09.980
mysterious, ever-present
memory.

00:40:09.980 --> 00:40:13.945
And the visual metaphor for
this kind of memory is,

00:40:13.945 --> 00:40:18.292
of course, the lake.
The lake is imagined to contain

00:40:18.292 --> 00:40:22.994
whole and undecayed all the
objects of the past that have

00:40:22.994 --> 00:40:26.985
been lost in it.
So memory is imagined in the

00:40:26.985 --> 00:40:31.776
same terms, so that you could
always bring them up to the

00:40:31.776 --> 00:40:35.369
surface and there they would be,
whole.

00:40:35.369 --> 00:40:38.959
So, the resurrection
imagined, if you run the film

00:40:38.959 --> 00:40:42.819
backward of the train slipping
in to the lake--I read that

00:40:42.819 --> 00:40:46.680
passage last time--the kind of
resurrection imagined,

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:51.570
is the way memory works.
But more specifically it's the

00:40:51.570 --> 00:40:54.280
way the language of memory
works.

00:40:54.280 --> 00:41:01.550
And I want to read my own
favorite passage.

00:41:01.550 --> 00:41:05.595
This is at the very end of the
novel, and I want you to think,

00:41:05.595 --> 00:41:08.772
as I read it,
about the difference between

00:41:08.772 --> 00:41:13.370
this passage and the one I read
from Bluest Eye about

00:41:13.370 --> 00:41:16.002
Pecola,
that passage of negativity

00:41:16.002 --> 00:41:19.208
about her being a kind of blank
or a negative,

00:41:19.208 --> 00:41:23.840
against which all other virtues
could be present in the world.

00:41:23.840 --> 00:41:28.130
So, think about that as I read
this, the bottom of 217:

00:41:28.130 --> 00:41:33.274
Since we are dead,
the house would be hers now

00:41:33.274 --> 00:41:36.949
[hers, Lucille].
Perhaps she is in the kitchen

00:41:36.949 --> 00:41:39.449
snuggling pretty daughters in
her lap.

00:41:39.449 --> 00:41:43.221
And perhaps now and then they
look at the black window to find

00:41:43.221 --> 00:41:45.880
out what their mother seems to
see there,

00:41:45.880 --> 00:41:49.286
and they see their own faces
and a face so like their

00:41:49.286 --> 00:41:52.429
mother's, so rapt and full of
tender watching,

00:41:52.429 --> 00:41:56.690
that only Lucille could think
the face was mine.

00:41:56.690 --> 00:42:00.004
If Lucille is there,
Sylvie and I have stood outside

00:42:00.004 --> 00:42:03.838
her window a thousand times and
we have thrown the side door

00:42:03.838 --> 00:42:07.152
open when she was upstairs
changing beds and we have

00:42:07.152 --> 00:42:11.246
brought in leaves and flung the
curtains and tipped the bud vase

00:42:11.246 --> 00:42:15.989
and somehow left the house again
before she could run downstairs,

00:42:15.989 --> 00:42:19.510
leaving behind us a strong
smell of lake water.

00:42:19.510 --> 00:42:23.530
She would sigh and think,
"they never change."

00:42:23.530 --> 00:42:27.788
Or imagine Lucille in Boston,
at a table in a restaurant

00:42:27.788 --> 00:42:31.469
waiting for a friend.
She is tastefully dressed,

00:42:31.469 --> 00:42:34.319
wearing, say,
a tweed suit with an amber

00:42:34.319 --> 00:42:38.046
scarf at the throat,
to draw attention to the red in

00:42:38.046 --> 00:42:41.621
her darkening hair.
Her water glass has left two

00:42:41.621 --> 00:42:45.523
thirds of a ring on the table
and she works at completing the

00:42:45.523 --> 00:42:49.651
circle with her thumbnail.
Sylvie and I do not flounce in

00:42:49.651 --> 00:42:52.938
through the door,
smoothing the skirts of our

00:42:52.938 --> 00:42:57.570
oversized coats and combing our
hair back with our fingers.

00:42:57.570 --> 00:43:02.378
We do not sit down at the table
next to hers and empty our

00:43:02.378 --> 00:43:06.490
pockets in a small,
damp heap in the middle of the

00:43:06.490 --> 00:43:10.781
table and sort out the gum
wrappers and ticket stubs and

00:43:10.781 --> 00:43:15.071
add up the coins and dollar
bills and laugh and add them

00:43:15.071 --> 00:43:17.310
again.
My mother, likewise,

00:43:17.310 --> 00:43:20.346
is not there,
and my grandmother in her house

00:43:20.346 --> 00:43:22.900
slippers with her pigtail
wagging,

00:43:22.900 --> 00:43:27.195
and my grandfather with his
hair combed flat against his

00:43:27.195 --> 00:43:31.570
brow does not examine the menu
with studious interest.

00:43:31.570 --> 00:43:37.200
We are nowhere in Boston.
However Lucille may look,

00:43:37.200 --> 00:43:42.070
she will never find us there,
or any trace or sign.

00:43:42.070 --> 00:43:46.951
We pause nowhere in Boston,
even to admire a store window

00:43:46.951 --> 00:43:51.309
and the perimeters of our
wandering are nowhere.

00:43:51.309 --> 00:43:55.009
No one watching this woman
smear her initials in the steam

00:43:55.009 --> 00:43:57.800
on her water glass with her
first finger,

00:43:57.800 --> 00:44:02.110
or slip cellophane packets of
oyster crackers into her handbag

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:06.562
for the seagulls could know how
her thoughts are thronged by our

00:44:06.562 --> 00:44:10.335
absence,
or know how she does not watch,

00:44:10.335 --> 00:44:13.165
does not listen,
does not wait,

00:44:13.165 --> 00:44:18.346
does not hope,
and always for me and

00:44:18.346 --> 00:44:24.245
Sylvie.
So, you see in that incredibly

00:44:24.245 --> 00:44:31.276
lyrical evocation of absence how
the very absence calls forth

00:44:31.276 --> 00:44:35.805
this lyric voice.
The structure is exactly the

00:44:35.805 --> 00:44:40.490
same as the one that Morrison
uses to describe what Pecola is

00:44:40.490 --> 00:44:44.940
to Claudia and Frieda and the
rest of their community.

00:44:44.940 --> 00:44:49.865
It's a way in which absence
calls forth the living essence

00:44:49.865 --> 00:44:53.927
of other people,
but here what's called forth is

00:44:53.927 --> 00:44:57.730
a sort of living essence of
imagination,

00:44:57.730 --> 00:45:03.706
a living essence of voice,
so that Sylvie and Ruth's

00:45:03.706 --> 00:45:10.972
absence for Lucille becomes the
very presence that they have to

00:45:10.972 --> 00:45:15.438
her.
There is a passage earlier in

00:45:15.438 --> 00:45:22.617
the novel where she describes
the condition of the body that

00:45:22.617 --> 00:45:28.579
matches up with this
understanding of absence.

00:45:28.579 --> 00:45:34.324
She's outside in the
orchard--this is on

00:45:34.324 --> 00:45:42.868
203--imagining the story of a
young girl in a lighted house

00:45:42.868 --> 00:45:46.480
that she sees.
Let's see.

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:49.010
It would be that kind of story,
a very melancholy story.

00:45:49.010 --> 00:45:51.363
Her hair,
which was as black as the sky,

00:45:51.363 --> 00:45:53.349
and so long that it swept after
her,

00:45:53.349 --> 00:45:55.369
a wind in the grass,
her fingers,

00:45:55.369 --> 00:45:59.029
which were sky black and so
fine and slender that they were

00:45:59.029 --> 00:46:01.489
only cold touch like drops of
rain,

00:46:01.489 --> 00:46:05.198
her step, which was so silent
that people were surprised when

00:46:05.198 --> 00:46:10.231
they even thought they heard it,
she would be transformed by the

00:46:10.231 --> 00:46:13.730
growth of light into a mortal
child.

00:46:13.730 --> 00:46:16.218
And, when she stood at the
bright window,

00:46:16.218 --> 00:46:18.769
she would find that the world
was gone,

00:46:18.769 --> 00:46:22.295
the orchard was gone,
her mother and grandmother and

00:46:22.295 --> 00:46:25.266
aunts were gone.
Like Noah's wife on the tenth

00:46:25.266 --> 00:46:28.601
or fifteenth night of rain,
she would stand in the window

00:46:28.601 --> 00:46:31.340
and realize that the world was
really lost.

00:46:31.340 --> 00:46:34.565
And those outside would
scarcely know her,

00:46:34.565 --> 00:46:39.065
so sadly was she changed.
Before she had been fleshed in

00:46:39.065 --> 00:46:43.024
air, and clothed in nakedness,
and mantled in cold,

00:46:43.024 --> 00:46:47.537
and her very bones were only
slender things like shards of

00:46:47.537 --> 00:46:50.217
ice.
She had haunted the orchard out

00:46:50.217 --> 00:46:52.819
of preference,
but she could walk into the

00:46:52.819 --> 00:46:55.040
lake without ripple or
displacement,

00:46:55.040 --> 00:46:57.769
and sail up the air invisibly
as heat.

00:46:57.769 --> 00:47:01.819
And now, lost to her kind,
she would almost forget them,

00:47:01.819 --> 00:47:05.942
and she would feed coarse food
to her coarse flesh and be

00:47:05.942 --> 00:47:10.411
almost satisfied.
And then Ruth meditates on her

00:47:10.411 --> 00:47:14.050
transformation in that time in
the orchard.

00:47:14.050 --> 00:47:16.710
If I had stayed there,
I might have discovered other

00:47:16.710 --> 00:47:17.956
things.
For example,

00:47:17.956 --> 00:47:21.816
I was hungry enough to begin to
learn that hunger has its

00:47:21.816 --> 00:47:25.400
pleasures, and I was happily at
ease in the dark.

00:47:25.400 --> 00:47:27.970
And, in general,
I could feel that I was

00:47:27.970 --> 00:47:31.199
breaking the tethers of need,
one by one.

00:47:31.199 --> 00:47:35.020
I would call this an anorexic
aesthetic.

00:47:36.849 --> 00:47:41.810
It's an aesthetic of starving
the self into invisibility so

00:47:41.810 --> 00:47:44.889
that the voice can become
present.

00:47:44.889 --> 00:47:48.876
So in this scene,
when she imagines the girl

00:47:48.876 --> 00:47:53.975
inside the house eating,
all that's outside the house is

00:47:53.975 --> 00:47:57.108
lost.
All she can see when she looks

00:47:57.108 --> 00:48:00.019
out her window is her own
reflection.

00:48:00.019 --> 00:48:07.159
But outside the house,
she is starved in to a kind of

00:48:07.159 --> 00:48:12.956
ethereal, full presence.
So the logic of absence--to

00:48:12.956 --> 00:48:17.574
bring it back around to this
question of identity and the

00:48:17.574 --> 00:48:22.439
identity of the voice--the logic
of absence starves away the

00:48:22.439 --> 00:48:26.150
person so that this fullness can
appear.

00:48:26.150 --> 00:48:32.612
And I think this is the dark
side of a novel that so many

00:48:32.612 --> 00:48:37.690
people initially read as a
feminist novel,

00:48:37.690 --> 00:48:42.308
a novel celebrating the
strength and the independence of

00:48:42.308 --> 00:48:45.845
women.
It turns to an aesthetic that

00:48:45.845 --> 00:48:49.699
has a kind of purchase in our
culture;

00:48:49.699 --> 00:48:56.221
that sense of anorexia blends
into the spiritual fullness of

00:48:56.221 --> 00:49:02.300
imagining memory as this
beautiful, lyrical presence.

00:49:02.300 --> 00:49:04.870
I think this is the complexity
of this novel;

00:49:04.870 --> 00:49:08.413
this is the tension.
It's also, in many ways,

00:49:08.413 --> 00:49:11.091
its beauty.
So, now I believe we have

00:49:11.091 --> 00:49:11.680
an answer.

00:49:15.320 --> 00:49:18.940
Jonathan Safran Foer.
That will be our novel.

00:49:18.940 --> 00:49:20.850
Eli, congratulations.

00:49:26.650 --> 00:49:29.000
Thank you very much.
Have a wonderful break.

